The managed reserve method is ``the beginning of a new approach to managing oysters and oyster disease,'' said Goldsborough of the Chesapeake Bay Foundation
By early next year, state and federal agencies expect to complete research on restoring the native oyster to the Chesapeake Bay.
``People suddenly woke up to the fact that they're going to be out of business this spring,'' said Bill Sieling, executive director of the Chesapeake Bay Seafood Industries Association, which represents seafood plants around the bay
``It's a beautiful concept in a sense because it's brought commercial interests and environmental interests together,'' said William Goldsborough, a senior scientist at the Chesapeake Bay Foundation
